Desponsata sorore regis. ‘ Dedit etiam juvenis rex praedictus sororem suam juniorem, dominam Johannem de Turre, in uxorem David filio Roberti de Brus, regis Scotiae, qui puer tunc erat quinque annorum, sicut ordinaverat mater sua, regina Angliae, quae tunc temporis totum regnum regebat. Celebratae vero sunt nuptiae solemniter apud Berwicum, Dominica die proxima ante festum sanctae Mariae Magdalenae [17th July].’—Chron. Lanercost, 261. The marriage, as well as the other articles os the treaty, was most unpopular in England: see Murimuth‚ p. 56, note 11. The princess was born in July, 1321 ; she was thus just seven years of age. The Brute chronicle (Harley MS. 2279) thus refers to the event z ‘And sn, thurgh hire cursede counsel, Pis David spousede, atte Berwyke, dame Johan atte pe Toure‚ pat was kyng Edwardis suster, as pe geste telleth, uppon Marie Maudeleyn daye [22 July], the yeer of grace mcccxxviij„ to grete harme and enpeyryng to alle pe kynges blode pat were os bat gentil ladie come. Allas pe tyme! for wonder moche was pat fayre damoseil dispergede, sith that she was mariede ayens alle pe comone assente of pe lordes os Engelonde.’ David’s nickname ‘drite on auter' is also given, but without explanation.
